{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659041","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659041"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:01:27+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:01:27+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20847"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20847","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20847"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96428"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13722"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20847"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79077"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11597"},{"type":"tags","id":"12331"},{"type":"tags","id":"12672"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33036"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33037"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96428","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96428"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes a mechanism that contributes to genomic instability in cancer?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduced expression of activation-induced cytosine deaminase","Upregulation of telomerase to prevent telomere shortening","Increased activity of DNA mismatch repair proteins","Loss of p53 function leading to defective cell cycle checkpoints","Enhanced nucleotide excision repair in response to UV damage"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of p53 function leading to defective cell cycle checkpoints\u003C/strong\u003E is a major mechanism contributing to genomic instability in cancer. p53 normally protects the genome by arresting cell division to allow time for DNA repair and by initiating apoptosis in irreparably damaged cells. When p53 function is lost, cells with severe genomic damage persist and accumulate additional mutations. TP53 is the most commonly mutated gene in cancer, making this the preeminent source of genomic instability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased activity of DNA mismatch repair proteins\u003C/strong\u003E would actually enhance genomic stability. Mismatch repair proteins act as \u0022spell checkers\u0022 during DNA replication, correcting errors such as G-T mispairing. Loss of these proteins leads to microsatellite instability and increased mutation rates, as seen in hereditary nonpolyposis colon cancer (Lynch syndrome).\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnhanced nucleotide excision repair in response to UV damage\u003C/strong\u003E would protect against genomic instability. Defects in nucleotide excision repair, as seen in xeroderma pigmentosum, lead to increased cancer risk due to inability to repair UV-induced DNA damage.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduced expression of activation-induced cytosine deaminase\u003C/strong\u003E would decrease genomic instability in lymphoid cells. AID normally creates controlled DNA breaks during immunoglobulin class switching and somatic hypermutation. Overexpression, not reduction, of AID contributes to lymphoid neoplasms.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpregulation of telomerase to prevent telomere shortening\u003C/strong\u003E actually promotes genomic stability in cancer cells. Telomere shortening in the absence of telomerase leads to break-fusion-breakage cycles and chromosomal instability. Cancer cells often upregulate telomerase to maintain telomere length and avoid this source of instability.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOther mechanisms contributing to genomic instability include defects in homologous recombination repair (as seen in BRCA1/2 mutations and Fanconi anaemia) and defective DNA polymerase proofreading function, which leads to accumulation of point mutations.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Genomic instability is a hallmark of cancer that accelerates the acquisition of driver mutations needed for tumour progression.","Loss of p53 function is the most common cause of genomic instability in cancers, leading to accumulation of mutations and chromosomal aberrations.","Defects in DNA repair mechanisms (mismatch repair, nucleotide excision repair, and homologous recombination) contribute to genomic instability and increased cancer risk."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 7; pages 313-314."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79077"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20847"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79077","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79077"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-01T13:55:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-01T13:56:15+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13722"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96428"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}